    18→https://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/753751f5-eda8-4145-a4b9-7ef51ca5e453
    19→
    20→## Usage
    21→
    22→```bash
    23→npm install input-otp
    24→```
    25→
    26→Then import the component.
    27→
    28→```diff
    29→+'use client'
    30→+import { OTPInput } from 'input-otp'
    31→
    32→function MyForm() {
    33→  return <form>
    34→+   <OTPInput maxLength={6} render={({slots})  => (...)} />
    35→  </form>
    36→}
    37→```
    38→
    39→## Default example
    40→
    41→The example below uses `tailwindcss` `@shadcn/ui` `tailwind-merge` `clsx`:
    42→
    43→```tsx
    44→'use client'
    45→import { OTPInput, SlotProps } from 'input-otp'
    46→<OTPInput
    47→  maxLength={6}
    48→  containerClassName="group flex items-center has-[:disabled]:opacity-30"
    49→  render={({ slots }) => (
    50→    <>
    51→      <div className="flex">
    52→        {slots.slice(0, 3).map((slot, idx) => (
    53→          <Slot key={idx} {...slot} />
    54→        ))}
    55→      </div>
    56→
    57→      <FakeDash />
    58→
    59→      <div className="flex">
    60→        {slots.slice(3).map((slot, idx) => (
    61→          <Slot key={idx} {...slot} />
    62→        ))}
    63→      </div>
    64→    </>
    65→  )}
    66→/>
    67→
    68→// Feel free to copy. Uses @shadcn/ui tailwind colors.
    69→function Slot(props: SlotProps) {
    70→  return (
    71→    <div
    72→      className={cn(
    73→        'relative w-10 h-14 text-[2rem]',
    74→        'flex items-center justify-center',
    75→        'transition-all duration-300',
    76→        'border-border border-y border-r first:border-l first:rounded-l-md last:rounded-r-md',
    77→        'group-hover:border-accent-foreground/20 group-focus-within:border-accent-foreground/20',
    78→        'outline outline-0 outline-accent-foreground/20',
    79→        { 'outline-4 outline-accent-foreground': props.isActive },
    80→      )}
    81→    >
    82→      <div className="group-has-[input[data-input-otp-placeholder-shown]]:opacity-20">
    83→        {props.char ?? props.placeholderChar}
    84→      </div>
    85→      {props.hasFakeCaret && <FakeCaret />}
    86→    </div>
    87→  )
    88→}
    89→
    90→// You can emulate a fake textbox caret!
    91→function FakeCaret() {
    92→  return (
    93→    <div className="absolute pointer-events-none inset-0 flex items-center justify-center animate-caret-blink">
    94→      <div className="w-px h-8 bg-white" />
    95→    </div>
    96→  )
    97→}
    98→
    99→// Inspired by Stripe's MFA input.
   100→function FakeDash() {
   101→  return (
   102→    <div className="flex w-10 justify-center items-center">
   103→      <div className="w-3 h-1 rounded-full bg-border" />
   104→    </div>
   105→  )
   106→}
   107→
   108→// tailwind.config.ts for the blinking caret animation.
   109→const config = {
   110→  theme: {
   111→    extend: {
   112→      keyframes: {
   113→        'caret-blink': {
   114→          '0%,70%,100%': { opacity: '1' },
   115→          '20%,50%': { opacity: '0' },
   116→        },
   117→      },
   118→      animation: {
   119→        'caret-blink': 'caret-blink 1.2s ease-out infinite',
   120→      },
   121→    },
   122→  },
   123→}
   124→
   125→// Small utility to merge class names.
   126→import { clsx } from 'clsx'
   127→import { twMerge } from 'tailwind-merge'
   128→
   129→import type { ClassValue } from 'clsx'
   130→
   131→export function cn(...inputs: ClassValue[]) {
   132→  return twMerge(clsx(inputs))
   133→}
   134→```
   135→
   136→## How it works
   137→
   138→There's currently no native OTP/2FA/MFA input in HTML, which means people are either going with 1. a simple input design or 2. custom designs like this one.
   139→This library works by rendering an invisible input as a sibling of the slots, contained by a `relative`ly positioned parent (the container root called _OTPInput_).
   140→
   141→## Features
   142→
   143→This is the most complete OTP input on the web. It's fully featured 
   144→
   145→<details>
   146→<summary>Supports iOS + Android copy-paste-cut</summary>
   147→
   148→https://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/bdbdc96a-23da-4e89-bff8-990e6a1c4c23
   149→
   150→</details>
   151→
   152→<details>
   153→<summary>Automatic OTP code retrieval from transport (e.g SMS)</summary>
   154→
   155→By default, this input uses `autocomplete='one-time-code'` and it works as it's a single input. 
   156→
   157→https://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/5705dac6-9159-443b-9c27-b52e93c60ea8
   158→
   159→</details>
   160→
   161→<details>
   162→<summary>Supports screen readers (a11y)</summary>
   163→
   164→Stripe was my first inspiration to build this library.
   165→
   166→Take a look at Stripe's input. The screen reader does not behave like it normally should on a normal single input.
   167→That's because Stripe's solution is to render a 1-digit input with "clone-divs" rendering a single char per div.
   168→
   169→https://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/3d127aef-147c-4f28-9f6c-57a357a802d0
   170→
   171→So we're rendering a single input with invisible/transparent colors instead.
   172→The screen reader now gets to read it, but there is no appearance. Feel free to build whatever UI you want:
   173→
   174→https://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/718710f0-2198-418c-8fa0-46c05ae5475d
   175→
   176→</details>
   177→
   178→<details>
   179→<summary>Supports all keybindings</summary>
   180→
   181→Should be able to support all keybindings of a common text input as it's an input.
   182→
   183→https://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/185985c0-af64-48eb-92f9-2e59be9eb78f
   184→
   185→</details>
   186→
   187→<details>
   188→<summary>Automatically optimizes for password managers</summary>
   189→
   190→
   191→For password managers such as LastPass, 1Password, Dashlane or Bitwarden, `input-otp` will automatically detect them in the page and increase input width by ~40px to trick the password manager's browser extension and prevent the badge from rendering to the last/right slot of the input.
   192→
   193→<img width="670" alt="image" src="https://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/9bb306ca-deff-4803-aa3d-148c594a540c">
   194→
   195→- **This feature is optional and it's enabled by default. You can disable this optimization by adding `pushPasswordManagerStrategy="none"`.**
   196→- **This feature does not cause visible layout shift.**
   197→
   198→### Auto tracks if the input has space in the right side for the badge
   199→
   200→https://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/bf01af88-1f82-463e-adf4-54a737a92f59
   201→
   202→</details>
   203→
   204→## API Reference
   205→
   206→### OTPInput
   207→
   208→The root container. Define settings for the input via props. Then, use the `render` prop to create the slots.
   209→
   210→#### Props
   211→
   212→```ts
   213→type OTPInputProps = {
   214→  // The number of slots
   215→  maxLength: number
   216→
   217→  // Render function creating the slots
   218→  render: (props: RenderProps) => React.ReactElement
   219→  // PS: Render prop is mandatory, except in cases
   220→  // you'd like to consume the original Context API.
   221→  // (search for Context in this docs)
   222→
   223→  // The class name for the root container
   224→  containerClassName?: string
   225→
   226→  // Value state controlling the input
   227→  value?: string
   228→  // Setter for the controlled value (or callback for uncontrolled value)
   229→  onChange?: (newValue: string) => unknown
   230→
   231→  // Callback when the input is complete
   232→  onComplete?: (...args: any[]) => unknown
   233→
   234→  // Where is the text located within the input
   235→  // Affects click-holding or long-press behavior
   236→  // Default: 'left'
   237→  textAlign?: 'left' | 'center' | 'right'
   238→
   239→  // Virtual keyboard appearance on mobile
   240→  // Default: 'numeric'
   241→  inputMode?: 'numeric' | 'text' | 'decimal' | 'tel' | 'search' | 'email' | 'url'
   242→
   243→  // Pro tip: input-otp export some patterns by default such as REGEXP_ONLY_DIGITS which you can import from the same library path
   244→  // Example: import { REGEXP_ONLY_DIGITS } from 'input-otp';
   245→  // Then use it as: <OTPInput pattern={REGEXP_ONLY_DIGITS}>
   246→  pattern?: string
   247→
   248→  // While rendering the input slot, you can access both the char and the placeholder, if there's one and it's active.
   249→  placeholder?: string
   250→
   251→  // Transfomer function that allows pasting, for example, "XXX-XXX" even though the input's regex/pattern doesn't allow hyphen and its max length is 6.
   252→  // Example: (pasted) => pasted.replaceAll('-', '')
   253→  pasteTransformer?: (pastedText: string) => string
   254→
   255→  // Enabled by default, it's an optional
   256→  // strategy for detecting Password Managers
   257→  // in the page and then shifting their
   258→  // badges to the right side, outside the input.
   259→  pushPasswordManagerStrategy?:
   260→    | 'increase-width'
   261→    | 'none'
   262→
   263→  // Enabled by default, it's an optional
   264→  // fallback for pages without JS.
   265→  // This is a CSS string. Write your own
   266→  // rules that will be applied as soon as
   267→  // <noscript> is parsed for no-js pages.
   268→  // Use `null` to disable any no-js fallback (not recommended).
   269→  // Default: `
   270→  // [data-input-otp] {
   271→  //   --nojs-bg: white !important;
   272→  //   --nojs-fg: black !important;
   273→  // 
   274→  //   background-color: var(--nojs-bg) !important;
   275→  //   color: var(--nojs-fg) !important;
   276→  //   caret-color: var(--nojs-fg) !important;
   277→  //   letter-spacing: .25em !important;
   278→  //   text-align: center !important;
   279→  //   border: 1px solid var(--nojs-fg) !important;
   280→  //   border-radius: 4px !important;
   281→  //   width: 100% !important;
   282→  // }
   283→  // @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
   284→  //   [data-input-otp] {
   285→  //     --nojs-bg: black !important;
   286→  //     --nojs-fg: white !important;
   287→  //   }
   288→  // }`
   289→  noScriptCSSFallback?: string | null
   290→}
   291→```
   292→
   293→## Examples
   294→
   295→<details>
   296→<summary>Automatic form submission on OTP completion</summary>
   297→
   298→```tsx
   299→export default function Page() {
   300→  const formRef = useRef<HTMLFormElement>(null)
   301→  const buttonRef = useRef<HTMLButtonElement>(null)
   302→
   303→  return (
   304→    <form ref={formRef}>
   305→      <OTPInput
   306→        // ... automatically submit the form
   307→        onComplete={() => formRef.current?.submit()}
   308→        // ... or focus the button like as you wish
   309→        onComplete={() => buttonRef.current?.focus()}
   310→      />
   311→
   312→      <button ref={buttonRef}>Submit</button>
   313→    </form>
   314→  )
   315→}
   316→```
   317→</details>
   318→
   319→<details>
   320→<summary>Automatically focus the input when the page loads</summary>
   321→
   322→```tsx
   323→export default function Page() {
   324→  return (
   325→    <form ref={formRef}>
   326→      <OTPInput
   327→        autoFocus
   328→        // Pro tip: accepts all common HTML input props...
   329→      />
   330→    </form>
   331→  )
   332→}
   333→```
   334→</details>
   335→
   336→<details>
   337→<summary>Usage with react-hook-form</summary>
   338→Just use it as a regular text input:
   339→
   340→```tsx
   341→const { register, handleSubmit } = useForm();
   342→// Then register it like a text input
   343→<InputOTP {...register("otp")} />
   344→```
   345→
   346→You can also use react-hook-form's Controller if needed:
   347→```tsx
   348→const { control } = useForm();
   349→// Then control it like a text input
   350→<Controller
   351→  name="customOTP"
   352→  control={control}
   353→  defaultValue=""
   354→  render={({ field }) => (
   355→    <OTPInput
   356→      {...field}
   357→      label="Custom OTP"
   358→    />
   359→  )}
   360→/>
   361→```
   362→</details>
   363→
   364→<details>
   365→<summary>Paste-transformers</summary>
   366→If you want to allow pasting of "XXX-XXX" even though the input's regex/pattern doesn't allow hyphen and its max length is 6, you can use the `pasteTransformer` prop.
   367→
   368→```tsx
   369→<OTPInput
   370→  // Transform the pasted text to parse hyphens but remove hyphens,
   371→  // so it fits into the input's pattern and max length.
   372→  pasteTransformer={(pasted) => pasted.replaceAll('-', '')}
   373→/>
   374→```
   375→</details>
   376→
   377→## Caveats
   378→
   379→<details>
   380→<summary>[Workaround] If you want to block specific password manager/badges:</summary>
   381→
   382→By default, `input-otp` handles password managers for you.
   383→The password manager badges should be automatically shifted to the right side.
   384→
   385→However, if you still want to block password managers, please disable the `pushPasswordManagerStrategy` and then manually block each PWM.
   386→
   387→```diff
   388→<OTPInput
   389→  // First, disable library's built-in strategy
   390→  // for shifting badges automatically
   391→- pushPasswordManagerStrategy="increase-width"
   392→+ pushPasswordManagerStrategy="none"
   393→  // Then, manually add specifics attributes
   394→  // your password manager docs
   395→  // Example: block LastPass
   396→+ data-lpignore="true" 
   397→  // Example: block 1Password
   398→+ data-1p-ignore="true"
   399→/>
   400→```
   401→</details>
   402→
   403→<details>
   404→<summary>[Setting] If you want to customize the `noscript` CSS fallback</summary>
   405→
   406→By default, `input-otp` handles cases where JS is not in the page by applying custom CSS styles.
   407→If you do not like the fallback design and want to apply it to your own, just pass a prop:
   408→
   409→```diff
   410→// This is the default CSS fallback.
   411→// Feel free to change it entirely and apply to your design system.
   412→const NOSCRIPT_CSS_FALLBACK = `
   413→[data-input-otp] {
   414→  --nojs-bg: white !important;
   415→  --nojs-fg: black !important;
   416→
   417→  background-color: var(--nojs-bg) !important;
   418→  color: var(--nojs-fg) !important;
   419→  caret-color: var(--nojs-fg) !important;
   420→  letter-spacing: .25em !important;
   421→  text-align: center !important;
   422→  border: 1px solid var(--nojs-fg) !important;
   423→  border-radius: 4px !important;
   424→  width: 100% !important;
   425→}
   426→@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
   427→  [data-input-otp] {
   428→    --nojs-bg: black !important;
   429→    --nojs-fg: white !important;
   430→  }
   431→}`
   432→
   433→<OTPInput
   434→  // Pass your own custom styles for when JS is disabled
   435→+ noScriptCSSFallback={NOSCRIPT_CSS_FALLBACK}
   436→/>
   437→```
   438→</details>
   439→
   440→<details>
   441→<summary>[Workaround] If you're experiencing an unwanted border on input focus:</summary>
   442→
   443→```diff
   444→<OTPInput
   445→  // Add class to the input itself
   446→+ className="focus-visible:ring-0"
   447→  // Not the container
   448→  containerClassName="..."
   449→/>
   450→```
   451→</details>
   452→
   453→<details>
   454→<summary>[Not Recommended] If you want to centralize input text/selection, use the `textAlign` prop:</summary>
   455→
   456→```diff
   457→<OTPInput
   458→  // customizable but not recommended
   459→+ textAlign="center"
   460→/>
   461→```
   462→
   463→NOTE: this also affects the selected caret position after a touch/click.
   464→
   465→`textAlign="left"`
   466→<img src="https://github.com/guilhermerodz/input-otp/assets/10366880/685a03df-2b69-4a36-b21c-e453f6098f79" width="300" />
   467→<br>
   468→
   469→`textAlign="center"`
